STAT 4181 Homework 3

Question A

library(astsa)
package astsa was built under R version 3.3.2
data(cmort)
plot(cmort)

acf(cmort)

pacf(cmort)

MAX_LAG <- 8
all_aic <- matrix(0,
                  nrow=MAX_LAG+1,
                  ncol=MAX_LAG+1)
for(p in 0:MAX_LAG){
  for(q in 0:MAX_LAG){
    all_aic[p+1,q+1] <- arima(cmort,order=c(p,0,q))$aic
  }
}

We get the lowest AIC is for p=6 and q=4. However, as we will see, this model is not fit properly, and has numerical issues.

cmort_best_model <- arima(cmort,order=c(6,0,4))
possible convergence problem: optim gave code = 1

We instead choose the next best model, which is the p=2, q=0 (i.e., AR(2)) model.

cmort_best_model <- arima(cmort,order=c(2,0,0))
predict(cmort_best_model,n.ahead = 12)$pred
Time Series:
Start = c(1979, 41) 
End = c(1979, 52) 
Frequency = 52 
 [1] 87.66207 86.85311 87.46615 87.37190 87.60258 87.66009 87.78688 87.86685
 [9] 87.95734 88.03163 88.10362 88.16744

Instead of using the for loop, we can make use of the auto.arima function in the forecast package. Note that we need to specify max.d=0 since we do not want to fit any ARIMA models with \(d>0\).

library(forecast)
Loading required package: zoo

Attaching package: zoo

The following objects are masked from package:base:

    as.Date, as.Date.numeric

Loading required package: timeDate
This is forecast 7.3 


Attaching package: forecast

The following object is masked from package:astsa:

    gas
auto.arima(cmort,max.d = 0)
Series: cmort

Coefficients:

      0.4301  0.4424    88.8538

This also gives us the AR(2) model.

Question B

library(readr)
library(zoo)
library(xts)
HW1_data_coindesk <- read_csv("~/Dropbox/Teaching/STAT 4181 - S17/Homework/HW1-data-coindesk.csv")
Parsed with column specification:
cols(
  Date = col_character(),
  `Close Price` = col_double()
)
HW1_data_coindesk$Date <- as.Date(HW1_data_coindesk$Date,
                    format="%m/%e/%y %H:%M")
bit_zoo <- zoo(x = HW1_data_coindesk$`Close Price`,
               order.by = HW1_data_coindesk$Date)
bit_xts <- as.xts(bit_zoo)
bitpre17 <- bit_xts['/2016']
library(forecast)
auto.arima(bitpre17)
Series: bitpre17 
ARIMA(5,2,0)                    

Coefficients:
          ar1      ar2      ar3      ar4      ar5
      -0.8616  -0.8099  -0.6023  -0.3793  -0.2012
s.e.   0.0298   0.0381   0.0418   0.0391   0.0313

sigma^2 estimated as 299.2:  log likelihood=-4668.94
AIC=9349.88   AICc=9349.96   BIC=9379.87

The best model is an ARI model with p=5, d=2.

forecasts <- rep(0,24)
for(i in 1:24){
  todays_date <- paste0("/2017-01-",i)
  bitpre17 <- bit_xts[todays_date]
  bitpre17_arima <- arima(bitpre17,order=c(5,2,0))
  
  forecasts[i] <- predict(bitpre17_arima,1)$pred
}
forecasts_xts <- xts(forecasts,
                     order.by = index(bit_xts["2017-01-02/25"]))
plot(bit_xts["2017-01-02/25"],ylim=c(700,1200))
lines(as.xts(forecasts_xts),col=2)

forecast_err <- bit_xts["2017-01-02/25"] - forecasts_zoo
